06042nam a2200769Ia 9789048556755DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485567557 a10.1515/97890485567552doi  a(DE-B1597)678308  a(OCoLC)1410764663  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aART0150002bisacsh00aRembrandt Seen Through Jewish Eyes :bThe Artist's Meaning to Jews from His Time to Ours /ced. by Mirjam Knotter, Gary Schwartz. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tJEWS AND JUDAISM IN REMBRANDT'S OWN WORLD -- tSephardi Jewish Life and Material Culture in Rembrandt's Time -- tRembrandt and His (Jewish) Neighbors: A Stroll Through the Neighborhood -- tMap with residents and owners of houses in and around the Jodenbreestraat in Rembrandt's time (ca. 1625-1658) -- tRembrandt's Other Jews: The Amsterdam Ashkenazim in the Seventeenth Century -- tSOCIETY, SPIRITUALITY, IMAGERY -- tRembrandt and Multicultural Amsterdam: Jews and Black People in Rembrandt's Art -- tRembrandt, Menasseh ben Israel and Spinoza -- tRembrandt, the Jews and Judaism -- tJewish Brides, Rabbis and Sitters in Rembrandt's Prints -- tJEWISH ARTISTS -- tModern Jewish Artists Discover Rembrandt -- tLaying it on Thick: British (Immigrant) Artists and their Rembrandt -- tRembrandt and Russian Jewish Artists -- tJEWISH COLLECTORS AND MUSEUMS -- tRembrandt as Seen by Jewish Museums -- tJewish Collectors Take Rembrandt to their Hearts -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aThe earliest painting by Rembrandt whose owner is documented depicts the prophet Balaam, on his way to blessing Israel. The man who bought it was a Sephardi Jew in the service of Cardinal Richelieu of France. The first known buyer of an etching plate by Rembrandt, depicting Abraham Dismissing Hagar and Ishmael, was a Sephardi Jew of Amsterdam. Seen through their eyes, Rembrandt was the creator of images with a special meaning to Jews. They have been followed through the centuries by Jewish collectors, Jewish art historians, Jewish artists who saw their own deepest concerns modelled in his art and life, and even prominent rabbis, one of whom said that Rembrandt was a Tzadik, a holy man blessed by God. This book is the first study in depth of the potent bond between Rembrandt and Jews, from his time to ours, a bond that has penetrated the image of the artist and the people alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aAUP Wetenschappelijk. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh  aRembrandt, Jewish artists, Jewish museums, art collectors, Russian museums.1 aGetashvili, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrigoryev, Roman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnotter, Mirjam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnotter, Mirjam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeguit, Guido, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNadler, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerlove, Shelley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchama, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwartz, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aS